<subSubSection pageId="163" pageNumber="766" type="distribution">
<caption inLine="true" pageId="163" pageNumber="766" startId="163.[784,956,1440,1474]" targetBox="[168,759,1217,1630]" targetPageId="163">
<paragraph blockId="163.[783,1376,1208,1632]" pageId="163" pageNumber="766">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[784,960,1440,1474]" pageId="163" pageNumber="766">Distribution.</emphasis>
Patchy butwidespread in savanna habitats from Sierra Leone E to South Sudan and extreme S Ethiopia, and S to Kenya and Tanzania; range possibly extends farther S to Malawi, Mozambique,
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="163.[167,1374,1636,2302]" box="[170,412,1636,1670]" pageId="163" pageNumber="766">and E Zimbabwe.</paragraph>
</caption>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="163" pageNumber="766" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="163.[167,1374,1636,2302]" pageId="163" pageNumber="766">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[170,418,1685,1710]" pageId="163" pageNumber="766">Descriptive notes.</emphasis>
Head—body 98-110 mm, tail 149-186 mm, ear 15-21 mm, hindfoot 22-27 mm; weight 31-60 g. Macmillan’s Thicket Rat has fur olive brown to gray above and bright rufous brown in rump area, with sharply demarcated white or creamy-white belly. Tail is very long (160% of head—body length), semi-prehensile, and tufted. Ears have a small rusty-colored post-auricular spot. Feet have four digits on forefoot and five on relatively short hindfoot,fifth digit longer and semi-opposable. Claws are short, as in all members of genus. Females have 1+2 = 3 pairs of nipples. Chromosomal complement has 2n = 68-76.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="163" pageNumber="766" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph blockId="163.[167,1374,1636,2302]" pageId="163" pageNumber="766">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[169,280,1992,2026]" pageId="163" pageNumber="766">Habitat.</emphasis>
Forested and riparian-forest habitats within savanna. Macmillan’s Thicket Rats may occupy holes in trees and in roofs of huts and houses.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
